<li id="r2123"} ">
<a href="#r2123" title="Permalink this reply" rel="bookmark">#8</a>
<img src="http://www.gravatar.com/avatar.php?gravatar_id=2c24211edec86c2f19c7fe54260b2893&amp;size=40" alt="" />
<h4 class="vcard"><span class="fn url"><a href="http://twitter.com/prisca_eyedea">prisca</a></span></h4>
<blockquote><p>Andy, thanks so much for posting the slides and transcript of your talk - looks beautiful :) Wonderful to be able to read your talk along with the visuals - thanks for sharing it with the rest of us, much appreciated :)</p>

<p>And what a great read! Great to get your thoughts on designing in the broswer. I&#8217;ve been going from sketchbook straight to the code and browser for designing for a while now. It started out of necessity initially with time being tight and me wanting to do a few &#8216;favours for friends&#8217;-type projects in the midst of other work. I noticed how much more efficient my workflow became - and also how the live previews were so much better for my clients, being able to discuss aspects like the browser differences as well as the nature and importance of fluid layouts was such a bonus that I stuck with it. <br />
I don&#8217;t think it works for all projects equally well - but when it does fit the project it is definitely my preferred choice of working now.</p>

<p>Thanks again, Andy :)
</p></blockquote>

<p><time datetime="2009-06-28" class="updated published">28th Jun 2009 <span class='value-title' title="2009-06-28"></span></time>
